    "reasoning": "1. **Analyze Requirements**: The module is a Moore State Machine representing a Lemming. \n   - States: Walking Left, Walking Right, Falling (while previously walking left), Falling (while previously walking right).\n   - Transitions: \n     - If walking left and `bump_left` is 1, switch to walking right.\n     - If walking left and `bump_right` is 1, switch to walking left (no change).\n     - If walking right and `bump_right` is 1, switch to walking left.\n     - If walking right and `bump_left` is 1, switch to walking right (no change).\n     - If `ground` is 0, enter 'Falling' state. The Lemming remembers its previous direction.\n     - When `ground` becomes 1 again, return to the previous walking state.\n     - Bumps while falling or during the transition cycle of ground reappearing do not change the 'intended' direction.\n   - Reset: `areset` is asynchronous positive edge triggered, initializing the Lemming to walk left.\n   - Output: Moore outputs (depend only on current state).\n\n2. **State Design**: \n   - `WALK_LEFT`: `walk_left=1`, `walk_right=0`, `aaah=0`.\n   - `WALK_RIGHT`: `walk_left=0`, `walk_right=1`, `aaah=0`.\n   - `FALL_LEFT`: `walk_left=0`, `walk_right=0`, `aaah=1` (intended to walk left).\n   - `FALL_RIGHT`: `walk_left=0`, `walk_right=0`, `aaah=1` (intended to walk right).\n\n3. **Transition Logic**:\n   - From `WALK_LEFT`: \n     - If `ground == 0` -> `FALL_LEFT`.\n     - Else if `bump_left == 1` -> `WALK_RIGHT`.\n     - Else -> `WALK_LEFT`.\n   - From `WALK_RIGHT`: \n     - If `ground == 0` -> `FALL_RIGHT`.\n     - Else if `bump_right == 1` -> `WALK_LEFT`.\n     - Else -> `WALK_RIGHT`.\n   - From `FALL_LEFT`: \n     - If `ground == 1` -> `WALK_LEFT`.\n     - Else -> `FALL_LEFT`.\n   - From `FALL_RIGHT`: \n     - If `ground == 1` -> `WALK_RIGHT`.\n     - Else -> `FALL_RIGHT`.\n\n4. **Refinement on Bumps**: The spec says 'Being bumped while falling does not affect the walking direction'. This means when in `FALL_LEFT` or `FALL_RIGHT`, the `bump` inputs are ignored for the purpose of direction, and we only look at `ground`. However, the spec also says: 'being bumped in the same cycle as ground disappears... or when the ground reappears... also does not affect the walking direction'. This implies the direction is determined at the moment of falling and stays that way until ground returns.\n\n5. **Implementation Details**:\n   - Use `always @(posedge clk or posedge areset)` for asynchronous reset.\n   - Use `always @(*)` for combinational next-state and output logic.\n   - Use `localparam` for state encoding.\n   - Use `initial` blocks to prevent X propagation for non-reset signals if necessary, though in this specific FSM, the asynchronous reset covers all states.\n\n6. **Syntax Advice**:\n   - Ensure all ports match the interface exactly.\n   - Use `logic` for all signals.\n   - Avoid `unique`, `inside`, or `case inside` syntax as per constraints.",
    "module": "module TopModule(\n    input  logic clk,\n    input  logic areset,\n    input  logic bump_left,\n    input  logic bump_right,\n    input  logic ground,\n    output logic walk_left,\n    output logic walk_right,\n    output logic aaah\n);\n\n    // State encoding\n    localparam STATE_WALK_LEFT  = 2'b00;\n    localparam STATE_WALK_RIGHT = 2'b01;\n    localparam STATE_FALL_LEFT  = 2'b10;\n    localparam STATE_FALL_RIGHT = 2'b11;\n\n    logic [1:0] state;\n    logic [1:0] state_next;\n\n    // Sequential logic for state transition\n    always @(posedge clk or posedge areset) begin\n        if (areset) begin\n            state <= STATE_WALK_LEFT;\n        end else begin\n            state <= state_next;\n        end\n    end\n\n    // Combinational logic for next state\n    always @(*) begin\n        state_next = state;\n        case (state)\n            STATE_WALK_LEFT:\n                if (!ground) begin\n                    state_next = STATE_FALL_LEFT;\n                end else if (bump_left) begin\n                    state_next = STATE_WALK_RIGHT;\n                end else begin\n                    state_next = STATE_WALK_LEFT;\n                end\n\n            STATE_WALK_RIGHT:\n                if (!ground) begin\n                    state_next = STATE_FALL_RIGHT;\n                end else if (bump_right) begin\n                    state_next = STATE_WALK_LEFT;\n                end else begin\n                    state_next = STATE_WALK_RIGHT;\n                end\n\n            STATE_FALL_LEFT:\n                if (ground) begin\n                    state_next = STATE_WALK_LEFT;\n                end else begin\n                    state_next = STATE_FALL_LEFT;\n                end\n\n            STATE_FALL_RIGHT:\n                if (ground) begin\n                    state_next = STATE_WALK_RIGHT;\n                end else begin\n                    state_next = STATE_FALL_RIGHT;\n                end\n\n            default:\n                state_next = STATE_WALK_LEFT;\n        endcase\n    end\n\n    // Combinational logic for Moore outputs\n    always @(*) begin\n        walk_left  = 1'b0;\n        walk_right = 1'b0;\n        aaah       = 1'b0;\n\n        case (state)\n            STATE_WALK_LEFT:\n                walk_left = 1'b1;\n            STATE_WALK_RIGHT:\n                walk_right = 1'b1;\n            STATE_FALL_LEFT,\n            STATE_FALL_RIGHT:\n                aaah = 1'b1;\n            default:\n                begin\n                    walk_left  = 1'b0;\n                    walk_right = 1'b0;\n                    aaah       = 1'b0;\n                end\n        endcase\n    end\n\nendmodule"
